## Regression Methods
- When you're trying to model a relationship between different variables in the data
- This encompasses the class of problem itself but also methods which are designed to solve that problem
- Regression usually involves some kind of minimisation of an error or a distance between the data and the fitted function which gives you a prediction
- i.e. create line of best fit and use to predict output

## Clustering Methods
- For when trying to organise the data into groups or clusters, which have some kind of common properties
- Looks at inherent structure of data
- Some methods have predefined number of clusters, some try to determine number of clusters automatically

## Decision Trees
- Decisions based on values in the data
- Such approach can result in decision tree method
- Branches respons to decisions you can takes based on data
- The final result can be classification or regression and applying it to some new data once you have trained a DT modelis inexpensive because you just need to follow branching of a tree

## Instance based learning
- Used for classification
- They don’t learn model, instead they select subset of data that is going to best represent whole dataset or sometimes keep the entire data set to make decision
- Called instance based approaches because they still somehow manipulate direct instance of the data
- Classification of the new data is then based on all of the closest or supporting instances in the subset
- Mostly differ by how they access the original data and how they measure similarity

## Bayesian Models
- Allows to update prediction that are made in light of new data which can be used to build a  statistical and probabilistic model of the data
- Idea is that you start from initial guess on what values potential model from the data could be
- Then evaluate probability that each data point belongs to each model and by observing actual model to which the datapoint belongs to a posteriori you can then adjust the probability of all the different models

## Dimensionality reduction
- When you have data that belongs to a very large dimensional space, but the task itself can actually be solved in a lower dimension space then you can try to reduce dimensionality, which will allow you to extract information most relevant to problem while maximising the information that you are actually retaining.
- This can be used for visualisation but to some extent you can also make classification or regression from lower dimensional space

## Artificial Neural Networks
- Enabled by the progress which has been made into a large scale optimisation where we can now handle something called back propagation in a large network of nodes from a graph where each of the nodes basically represents a transformation which is applied to the data
- Initially transformations were made to simulate neurons in brain, but actually work in very different way

## Deep Learning
- When you are making very large model with neural network, you can handle extremely complex transformations, also add more layers between input and output
- Have transformations not directly connected to I/O layers
